title: King County Directors Association -  Digital copies of all LEGAL INVOICES and/or PAYMENTS to Attorneys and/or Law Firms (2020-2024)

communications.subject: Washington Public Records Act Request: King County Directors Association -  Digital copies of all LEGAL INVOICES and/or PAYMENTS to Attorneys and/or Law Firms (2020-2024)
communications.communication:
June 24, 2024

Public Records request for digital copies of all LEGAL INVOICES and/or PAYMENTS to Attorneys and/or Law Firms (2020-2024)

To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act [RCW 42.56] I hereby request digital copies the following public records:

1. Digital copies of any/all invoices or bills for any/all legal services or legal representation provided to your AGENCY, your AGENCY BOARD OF DIRECTORS, and/or AGENCY employees or representatives.

2. Digital copies of any/all payments made by your AGENCY for any/all legal services provided to the AGENCY or AGENCY employees or AGENCY representatives.

3. Digital copies of any/all emails, texts, and/or communications of any kind regarding legal invoices and/or payment for legal services of any kind made by your AGENCY.

DATE RANGE

The date range for this request is January 1, 2020 to June 24, 2024.

RECORDS INSTALLMENTS - ORDER OF PRODUCTION – REASONABLE ESTIMATE OF TIME

If production of responsive records will be completed in multiple installments, please begin by producing records in REVERSE CHRONOLOGICAL FORMAT BY DATE. The most recent public records should be produced first and the oldest records produced last by date.

Please provide a “reasonable” estimate of time your agency intends to produce a first installment of records as per WAC 44-14-04003 (7) and RCW 42.56.520(1)(c). This time estimate should be an actual date such as May 31, 2024 rather than an undefined block of time in the future such as “within the next six months.” (Hikel v. City of Lynnwood, Dec. 27, 2016)

DEFINITION OF RECORDS AND WRITINGS

RECORDS AND WRITINGS as defined by RCW 42.56.010(4): any handwriting, typewriting, printing, photostating, photographing, and every other means of recording any form of communication or representation including, but not limited to, letters, words, pictures, sounds, or symbols, or combination thereof, and all papers, maps, magnetic or paper tapes, photographic films and prints, motion picture, film and video recordings, magnetic or punched cards, discs, drums, diskettes, sound recordings, and other documents including existing data compilations from which information may be obtained or translated.

PRODUCTION PROCESSING AND DELIVERY OF ELECTRONIC RECORDS

Please provide all records in their native electronic format. Please do not instead create new records by printing electronic files then scanning and printing the newly scanned prints.

Washington State Law is clear that the use of 3rd party “portals” (Such as GOVQA) for a public records request is optional for the requestor. Respectfully I decline. Please provide all records electronically via direct email attachment to this email address.

Please do not register this requestor for, nor direct this requestor to the use of any 3rd party commercial portal including but not limited to FOIAOnline, GovQA, NextRequest, FOIAExpress, JustFOIA FOIADirect, WebForm, or any other online service other than a direct NO PASSWORD REQUIRED, NO REGISTRATION REQUIRED, internet cloud-based download link, or electronic email.

Do not send any portion of this public records request to any 3rd party for-profit corporation such as GOVQA, a Grannicus Corporation or NEXT-REQUEST.

Do not register this request with any for profit portal or 3rd party organization such as GOVQA, a Grannicus Corporation, or NEXT-REQUEST.

PUBLIC RECORDS REQUESTS SUBMITTED VIA EMAIL

RCW 42.56.080 - Identifiable records—Facilities for copying—Availability of public records.

"...Agencies shall honor requests received in person during an agency's normal office hours, or by mail or email, for identifiable public records unless exempted by provisions of this chapter. No official format is required for making a records request; however, agencies may recommend that requestors submit requests using an agency provided form or web page."

This public records request is being made via email. This public records request will be honored and fulfilled by your agency via email as requested or relief will be sought per statute.

NATIVE ELECTRONIC FORMAT

Please provide all identified public records in their NATIVE electronic format, either .pst file or .pdf/ .pdf PORTFOLIO file. Please provide all electronic records in the fewest number of individual files as per native format or use free .zip or digital compression in each installment for the fewest number of total records and the most economical calculation of any applicable public records fees.

FEES
In the event that there are fees, please inform us of the total charges in advance of fulfilling the request in strict compliance with all provisions of the Washington State Public Records Act.

EXEMPTION LOGS
Please ensure all redactions or exemptions claimed by your agency in the production of responsive records are accompanied by a complete and detailed exemption log noting the valid legal reason for each exemption at each redaction location in the record produced, as well as the specific number of pages if any that your agency redacts or withholds in their entirety. Each redaction should be noted by footnote or by a clear reference to the specific justification for that redaction, and only the minimal exempt portion of any record may be withheld.

COMMERCIAL PURPOSE DECLARATION
The Washington State Public Records Act prohibits the disclosure of “lists of individuals” for a commercial purpose (RCW 42.56.070(8)). I declare this public records request is not being made for any commercial purpose whatsoever. Also, this public records request is not being made for a "list of individuals." This declaration satisfies all requirements of RCW 42.56 regarding prohibitions on lists and commercial purposes. No additional commercial purpose declaration will be completed for this public records request.

PRESERVATION OF PUBLIC RECORDS *** ANTICIPATE LITAGATION ***

WAC 44-14-03005 RETENTION OF PUBLIC RECORDS

The lawful destruction of public records is governed by retention schedules. The unlawful destruction of public records can be a crime. RCW 40.16.010 and 40.16.020. An agency is prohibited from destroying a public record, even if it is about to be lawfully destroyed under a retention schedule, if a public records request has been made for that record. RCW 42.56.100. Additional retention requirements might apply if the records may be relevant to actual or anticipated litigation. The agency is required to retain the record until the record request has been resolved.

Note: An agency can be found to violate the Public Records Act and be subject to the attorneys' fees and penalty provision if it prematurely destroys a requested record after a request is made. See Yacobellis v. City of Bellingham, 55 Wn. App. 706, 780 P.2d 272 (1989). However, it is not a violation of the Public Records Act if a record is destroyed prior to an agency's receipt of a public records request for that record. Bldg. Indus. Ass'n of Wash. v. McCarthy, 152 Wn. App. 720, 218 P.3d 196 (2009); West v. Dep't of
Nat. Res., 163 Wn. App. 238, 258 P.3d 78 (2011). The Public Records Act (chapter 42.56 RCW) and the records retention statutes (chapter 40.14 RCW) are two different laws.

COMMUNICATION VIA EMAIL

Please send all requests for clarification, status updates, and production of responsive electronic documents via direct email reply.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. We look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Good Luck.

Attention Requester,



The purpose of this email is to acknowledge receipt of your Public Records Act request to King County Directors Association dated June 24, 2024, pursuant to RCW 42.56.520. KCDA's local public records policy can be found here: https://www.kcda.org/file%20library/public%20records%20policy%20and%20procedures/kcda_public_records_policy_and_procedures.pdf. KCDA estimates that all records responsive to your request will be made available to you no later than December 24th, 2029. Pursuant to RCW 42.56.520, this time may be needed in order to locate and assemble documents responsive to your request; to notify third persons affected by the request; and to determine whether any of the information requested is exempt from public disclosure. KCDA will produce responsive, non-exempt records in installments. We estimate that the first installment will be produced no later than 90 days. You will be notified of any applicable charges prior to production of each installment.





Kindest regards,

Kristen Deskin, SHRM-SCP

Attention Requester,

We are following up on your request made on 6/24/2024.

The estimated fees associated with coping files for this request is $14. The estimated fees associated with scanning files for this request is $2. This is a total fee estimate for this public records request of $16.

A 10% deposit for the estimated charges is required before further work on this request commences. Please mail a check for at least $1.60 to KCDA, or schedule a time to come pay cash in person: 18639 80th Ave S. Kent WA, 98032 during regular business hours. You may choose to pay the estimate in full and any surplus payment of actual fees upon final delivery will be refunded. You also have the option to amend your request in order to avoid or reduce the cost of a customized service charge.

You have 30 calendar days to pay the deposit or amend this request. If you do not respond within 30 days, KCDA will believe that it has fulfilled your request by:

  *   Notifying you on 09/03/2024 that you needed pay a deposit or amend your request and you failing to do so.


Therefore, if the deposit is not paid nor the request amended, KCDA will officially close this request as of 10/04/2024 and will provide no further responses to this request. If you believe KCDA has closed this request in error, have questions, or need clarification concerning this request, please respond to this e-mail within 30 calendar days. The Public Records Acts gives the requestor one year from the date an agency closes a records request to file in court an allegation that the agency violated the Act. For this records request, that opportunity would expire one year from closure of the request on 10/04/2024 should no payment or amendment be provided.




Kindest regards,

Kristen Deskin, SHRM-SCP

The actual cost of records production was $10.16.

Per KCDA’ s Public Records Act Policy and Procedure and RCW 42.56.120, the costs for producing copies of records include the following:

Cost for Electronic Records
Ten cents per page for public records scanned into an electronic format or for the use of KCDA equipment to scan the records; Five cents per each four electronic files or attachment uploaded to email, cloud-based data storage service, or other means of electronic delivery; Ten cents per gigabyte for the transmission of public records in an electronic format or for the use of KCDA equipment to send the records electronically; and The actual cost of any digital storage media or device provided by KCDA, the actual cost of any container or envelope used to mail the copies to the requestor, and the actual postage or delivery charge.

Your request produced 87 pages of hard-copy records which need to be scanned to produce electronically, resulting in copying costs of $8.70. There are also 117 originally-digital electronic files to be provided electronically, resulting in copying costs of $ 1.46. The data delivery file of 0.052321 gigabytes has negligible fees. The total cost of this records request is $10.16

 You paid $16 as the estimated cost of which $5.84 is due back to you, where would you like your refund check sent and whom should it be made out too? 

This completes KCDA’s response to your request dated June 24, 2024. KCDA has closed your request and no additional records will be produced in response to this request. With the closing of your request, the PRA’s one-year statute of limitations to seek judicial review of KCDA’s fulfillment of your request has started to run, as KCDA does not intend to take further action on your request. Please advise if you believe that KCDA’s determination that your request has been completely fulfilled is in error or if you have any questions.

Kindest regards,
Kristen Deskin, SHRM-SCP
Human Resources Manager
|Ph: 425-251-8115 x 126 | Fax: 253-395-5402 |

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: DHS FOIA Office Budgeting Records
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

On behalf of the #DetentionKills Transparency Initiative, I request: 

1. Any record submitted to DHS HQ (including Congressional Affairs, Management & Analysis, and the Secretary and appropriate under-Secretary’s offices, DHS FOIA) by DHS agency subcomponents CBP, OIG, ICE, and USCIS that seek or justify requests for additional appropriated funds from Congress or in the Presidential budget proposal to help these subcomponents’ FOIA offices clear their backlogs, shorten processing times, process and release more records, and avoid costly FOIA litigation. Please task a search for the budget cycles covering fiscal years (FY) 19, 20, 21, 22, and 23. 

2. Any record showing requested budget increases for DHS, ICE, CBP, OIG or USCIS FOIA offices that were not fulfilled by Congress in the appropriations legislation for FY19-22. 

3. Any record showing the amount of additional appropriated funds estimated to be necessary to reduce the current backlogs, shorten processing times, and avoid costly litigation involving FOIA processing by CBP, ICE, OIG, DHS, and USCIS during FY19-23. 

4. Any record of DHS acknowledging, approving, or directing its agency subcomponents’ FOIA offices (ICE, OIG, CBP, USCIS, or DHS) to “process” only  500 pages of records per month in litigation.

5. Any record showing DHS agency subcomponents’ FOIA Office determinations that they  lack adequate resources to fulfill their statutory timing obligations were communicated by those agencies to DHS leadership and budgeting personnel. The subcomponents to be queried are iCE, CBP, OIG, USCIS, and DHS HQ.  Please query FY19-23.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Andrew Free

communications.subject: RE: Freedom of Information Act Request #2022-HQFO-00867
communications.communication:
Dear Mr. Wolfrey: 

I hereby appeal the agency’s “too-broad” determination because it does not comport with 6 C.F.R. 5.3(b). I further appeal  the agency’s failure to categorize this “too-broad” determination as a denial and notify me of my right to appeal. And I appeal the agency’s failure to task an adequate search in response to this request. 

6 CFR Section 5.3(b) provides: 

(b) Description of records sought. Requesters must describe the records sought in sufficient detail to enable DHS personnel to locate them with a reasonable amount of effort. A reasonable description contains sufficient information to permit an organized, non-random search for the record based on the component's filing arrangements and existing retrieval systems. To the extent possible, requesters should include specific information that may assist a component in identifying the requested records, such as the date, title or name, author, recipient, subject matter of the record, case number, file designation, or reference number. Requesters should refer to appendix I of this subpart for additional component-specific requirements. In general, requesters should include as much detail as possible about the specific records or the types of records that they are seeking. Before submitting their requests, requesters may contact the component's FOIA Officer or FOIA public liaison to discuss the records they are seeking and to receive assistance in describing the records. If after receiving a request, a component determines that it does not reasonably describe the records sought, the component should inform the requester what additional information is needed or why the request is otherwise insufficient. Requesters who are attempting to reformulate or modify such a request may discuss their request with the component's designated FOIA Officer, its FOIA Public Liaison, or a representative of the DHS Privacy Office, each of whom is available to assist the requester in reasonably describing the records sought.

I am searching in vain to find any contact information you provided in your April 22, 2022, that would allow me, as a requestor, to “discuss [my] request with the component’s designated FOIA Officer, its FOIA Public Liaison, or a representative of the DHS FOIA Privacy Office, each of whom is available to assist [me] in reasonably describing the records sought.” 

DHS has offered no contact information in this letter for its Designated FOIA Officer, its FOIA Public Liaison, or a “representative of the DHS FOIA Privacy Office,” and as such, none of them are “available to assist” as your own regulations require. 

Please promptly remand this appeal with instructions to comply with the Department’s own FOIA regulations and the Act. 

Many thanks, 

Andrew Free
#DetentionKills Transparency Initiative
Al Otro Lado.

communications.communication:
You have reached the SecureRelease™ Support Desk.

The purpose of this inbox is to provide technical support for the SecureRelease FOIA Request Portal website (https://www.securerelease.us/).



SecureRelease Support is not involved with the processing or prioritization of requests, and this inbox is not monitored by agency personnel. To ask for an update or discuss the specifics of your request(s), you must contact the agency directly.


If you submitted your request(s) through the SecureRelease™ Request Portal<https://www.securerelease.us/> or to a participating agency using FOIA.gov, you may use the SecureRelease Portal Messages feature to send electronic correspondence and attachments directly to the agency.



To send a portal message:



  1.  Sign in to the SecureRelease™ Request Portal: https://www.securerelease.us/account-page/sign-in/
  2.  Click the My Requests icon
  3.  Locate the request you wish to inquire about, and click on the Request Number
  4.  From the request screen, click the Messages icon at the top of the page
  5.  Click the Add Message button at the upper right
  6.  Complete the required Message Fields
  7.  Drag and drop any Files you wish to attach into the file upload box (Optional)
     *   Maximum of 25 files can be attached to a message, and total file size cannot be more than 100 mb. Supported file formats: DOC, DOCX, XLS, XLSX, TXT, PDF, JPG, PNG, BMP and TIF/TIFF
  8.  Click Send
  9.  Return to the Messages tab within your Request to access outgoing and incoming messages


Should you have an inquiry related to your SecureRelease user account or concerning www.securerelease.us<http://www.securerelease.us>, please email us with the relevant details and a member of our support team will be happy to assist.



Take care,


SecureRelease™ Support Team
securereleasesupportteam@deloitte.com<mailto:securereleasesupportteam@deloitte.com>

title: mspy and brainstack records (Chicago Police Department)

communications.subject: Illinois Freedom of Information Act. Request: mspy and brainstack records (Chicago Police Department)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Illinois Freedom of Information Act., I hereby request the following records:

The requested records are all those, for the period between January 1, 2018 and the date on which this request is processed, describing and relating to the relationship between this agency and Brainstack, LLC and any relationships between any representative of either entity.
Responsive records include, but are not limited to, the following:
• All documents concerning or mentioning Brainstack, LLC and any representative thereof, including all documentation regarding mSpy and any other service or software provided by or created by Brainstack, LLC
CONTRACT AND AGREEMENTS
• All contracts, memorandums of understanding, and any other written agreements between this agency and Brainstack, including all associated amendments, exhibits, and supplemental and supporting documentation.
FINANCIAL MATERIALS
• All financial documents or records of financial transactions, exchanges or obligations related to the relationship between the aforementioned entities. Responsive materials include all invoices, bills, receipts, check stubs, or any other records, including those possessed in an electronic format. This also includes any Requests for Proposal and bidding materials provided by Brainstack and any other entities responding to the same Request for Proposal or equivalent procurement request.
MARKETING and PROMOTION MATERIALS
• All promotional, descriptive, and marketing materials in the possession of this agency related to and/or referencing “Brainstack” and/or “mSpy.” This includes all presentations, marketing materials, technical documentation, proposals, or similar records shared with this agency and/or any representative thereof by Brainstack and/or any representative thereof.
GUIDING DOCUMENTATION and POLICIES
• All policies, memorandums of understanding, and other guidance materials generated by this agency and/or any entity operating on its behalf or to its benefit (including, but not limited to, any unions, community groups, other government agencies, or individuals) regarding the acquisition and use of any data or services provided by Brainstack or any subdivision thereof. Responsive materials include, but are not limited to, any data-sharing agreements, terms of use, licensing agreements, and any other guiding materials.
• All user manuals, other guidance materials, help documents, or related materials obtained from Brainstack or the mSpy platform (hosted at www.mspy.com )
DOCUMENTATION OF USE
• Any query logs and other data obtained from the mSpy platform, including any “Signal List” CSV documents generated by the platform. Should query logs exist for any other platform, service, or software created and/or provided by Brainstack, these materials are also responsive to this request.
• Any audits and reports of audits of use of the mSpy platform
COMMUNICATIONS
• All written communications, emails, and attachments between this agency and any representative thereof and Brainstack and any representative thereof. Responsive materials include, but are not limited to, all communications sent to and from any “@brainstack.net” or “@mspy.com” email address, 
All written communications, emails, and attachments containing and/or referencing any of the following terms:
Brainstack
mSpy
NIT 
Network Investigative Technique 
Malware
Spyware 
Remote monitoring tool 
Phone tracker 
keylogger 
We ask that these materials be provided on a rolling basis; as your office collects and reviews records, we would appreciate it if your office would provide those materials to us incrementally.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Cooper Quintin

communications.subject: Non-Commercial FOIA Request :: P974278-082124
communications.communication:
Dear Cooper: 
 
Thank you for your interest in information from the Chicago Police Department. Your FOIA request has been received and is being processed. Your FOIA Center reference number for tracking purposes is: P974278-082124 
You have requested the following records: To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Illinois Freedom of Information Act., I hereby request the following records:

The requested records are all those, for the period between January 1, 2018 and the date on which this request is processed, describing and relating to the relationship between this agency and Brainstack, LLC and any relationships between any representative of either entity.
Responsive records include, but are not limited to, the following:
• All documents concerning or mentioning Brainstack, LLC and any representative thereof, including all documentation regarding mSpy and any other service or software provided by or created by Brainstack, LLC
CONTRACT AND AGREEMENTS
• All contracts, memorandums of understanding, and any other written agreements between this agency and Brainstack, including all associated amendments, exhibits, and supplemental and supporting documentation.
FINANCIAL MATERIALS
• All financial documents or records of financial transactions, exchanges or obligations related to the relationship between the aforementioned entities. Responsive materials include all invoices, bills, receipts, check stubs, or any other records, including those possessed in an electronic format. This also includes any Requests for Proposal and bidding materials provided by Brainstack and any other entities responding to the same Request for Proposal or equivalent procurement request.
MARKETING and PROMOTION MATERIALS
• All promotional, descriptive, and marketing materials in the possession of this agency related to and/or referencing “Brainstack” and/or “mSpy.” This includes all presentations, marketing materials, technical documentation, proposals, or similar records shared with this agency and/or any representative thereof by Brainstack and/or any representative thereof.
GUIDING DOCUMENTATION and POLICIES
• All policies, memorandums of understanding, and other guidance materials generated by this agency and/or any entity operating on its behalf or to its benefit (including, but not limited to, any unions, community groups, other government agencies, or individuals) regarding the acquisition and use of any data or services provided by Brainstack or any subdivision thereof. Responsive materials include, but are not limited to, any data-sharing agreements, terms of use, licensing agreements, and any other guiding materials.
• All user manuals, other guidance materials, help documents, or related materials obtained from Brainstack or the mSpy platform (hosted at www.mspy.com )
DOCUMENTATION OF USE
• Any query logs and other data obtained from the mSpy platform, including any “Signal List” CSV documents generated by the platform. Should query logs exist for any other platform, service, or software created and/or provided by Brainstack, these materials are also responsive to this request.
• Any audits and reports of audits of use of the mSpy platform
COMMUNICATIONS
• All written communications, emails, and attachments between this agency and any representative thereof and Brainstack and any representative thereof. Responsive materials include, but are not limited to, all communications sent to and from any “@brainstack.net” or “@mspy.com” email address,
All written communications, emails, and attachments containing and/or referencing any of the following terms:
Brainstack
mSpy
NIT
Network Investigative Technique
Malware
Spyware
Remote monitoring tool
Phone tracker
keylogger
We ask that these materials be provided on a rolling basis; as your office collects and reviews records, we would appreciate it if your office would provide those materials to us incrementally.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Cooper Quintin

Upload documents directly: https://accounts.muckrock.com/accounts/login/?next=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.muckrock.com%2Faccounts%2Flogin%2F%3Fnext%3D%252Faccounts%252Fagency_login%252Fchicago-police-department-503%252Fmspy-and-brainstack-records-chicago-police-department-172142%252F%253Femail%253Dfoia%252540chicagopolice.org&url_auth_token=AAAjxjMtpIpF_W_lFWW9xxGvJO8%3A1sgxui%3AaW9Xp5NfJ8QK-WRhJrMVqrGq3_-AiR_ZTGYPIyOkwqo 
Chicago Police Department (CPD) responds to all public records requests in accordance with the Illinois Freedom of Information Act (FOIA), 5 ILCS 140/1 et seq.  If further time is needed to assemble and copy all documents responsive to your FOIA request, we will contact you with a time estimate and a request to extend. You can monitor the progress of your request at the link below and you’ll receive an email when your request has been completed. Thank you for using the Chicago FOIA Center.

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: Third Party Investigative Platform (Purchase and Contract records) (Alameda Police Department)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the records listed below regarding the following four software programs: 

• Thompson Reuters Clear (https://legal.thomsonreuters.com/en/products/clear)
• LexisNexis Accurint (https://www.accurint.com/)
• TransUnion TLOxp, which may also be part of the TruLookup system (https://www.tlo.com/law-enforcement)
• SoundThinking CrimeTracer, which was formerly a product called COPLINK X (https://www.soundthinking.com/law-enforcement/crime-analysis-crimetracer/) from the company formerly known as ShotSpotter

For each of the above mentioned platforms, please provide the following records: 

• CONTRACTS AND AGREEMENTS —  All contracts (as well as associated amendments, attachments, and exhibits) and agreements related to the acquisition and use of these "software" programs.
• PURCHASE INFORMATION — All invoices and purchase information for costs and products associated with the above-referenced platforms.

Please provide responsive materials for the period from January 1, 2021 through the date this request is processed. 

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Aaron Blum

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: FBI: Cartoonist Theodore Stanley (Ted) Richards
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Bureau records related to a cartoonist and web designer named Theodore Stanley "Ted" Richards. Richards (born October 20th, 1946 - died April 21st, 2023) was a cartoonist in the 1960s and 70s. His work was frequently featured in publications such as The Berkeley Tribe. His death was widely reported, and a news report regarding his passing should be attached, and can be viewed at:

https://www.dailycartoonist.com/index.php/2023/04/24/ted-richards-rip/

This request is for any and all records about the Cartoonist Theodore Stanley "Ted" Richards from any and all FBI offices, including HQ, field offices, legal attaches, and facilities that maintain records under the FBI’s control. Please conduct a thorough search for any records on Richards held by the Cincinnati, San Francisco and Seattle field offices. According to a blog post I just read, it is important that I state the following: "As you know, your agency is required to search the records stored at NARA’s Washington Records Center in Suitland, MD, but still technically under your agency’s control. For more information see 36 CFR 1250.8" Please also conduct a physical search of records at NARA's Washington Records Center in Suitland, for any records or documents related to Theodore Stanley "Ted" Richards. 

Please include all potentially responsive materials, including but not limited to all communications, reports, inquiries, investigations, photographs, audio files, video files, memos, directives, etc. Please include all materials found in other subject files and all materials associated with any potentially-related names and any other known aliases, nicknames, code names, or any other identifying pseudonyms or references utilized by this agency. Please consult the Central Records System and records, the Electronic Surveillance (ELSUR) Data Management System and records, Microphone Surveillance (MISUR) records, Physical Surveillance (FISUR) records, Technical Surveillance (TESUR) records, and all available cross-reference indices, databases, and records, in addition to any other locations containing potentially-responsive materials related to Theodore Stanley "Ted" Richards. 

Please include a search of any records or documents understood to be, or colloquially referred to as "COINTELPRO records" under the bureau's custody that could be construed as responsive to a request for records related to Theodore Stanley "Ted" Richards. Please note, there appears to have been a previous FOIA request with the bureau for records related to The Berkeley Tribe (FOIA: 1394913-0). Much of that file, which is currently accessible on the Internet Archive, appears to be heavily redacted. Please re-examine The Berkeley Tribe release in relation to the release of documents related to Theodore Richards. 

If the bureau cannot fulfill certain parts of this request or if certain portions must be redacted, please provide any reasonable segregable portion of a requested record after removing or redacting those portions claimed to be exempt, explain in writing the justification for redacting the record, indicate the extent of any redactions on the portion of the record which is made available or published and where technically feasible indicate on the redacted portion itself the specific exemption(s) claimed.

Thank you for the work that the bureau does, and for the bureau's commitment to transparency. I look forward to the resolution of this request.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Robert Delaware

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: FOIA Requests (Occupational Safety and Health Administration)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

I am searching for any and all documents regarding, evidencing, or detailing violations, warnings, cautions, fines, penalties, judgments, agency determinations, and/or enforcement inspections against the following entities at any time from 1972 to present:

-	BNSF Railway 
-	Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railway
-	Burlington Northern Railroad
-	St. Louis–San Francisco Railway

This requests specifically seeks, but is not limited to, any records regarding violations, warnings, cautions, fines, testing, inspection, citations, survey work, agency recommendations/plans of action, or any communications with the above-named entity(-ies) regarding or related to violations of air quality, pollution, waste disposal, respiratory protection, workplace safety, and asbestos-related standards.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Kevin LaMarca

--- Please respond above this line --- 
10/09/2024 
Miriam Bhimani 
Dear Miriam Bhimani: 
RE: Chicago Public Schools FOIA Request N016180-092424 
Thank you for using the Chicago Public Schools FOIA Center. You requested the following: 
To Whom It May Concern: 

Pursuant to the Illinois Freedom of Information Act., I hereby request the following records: 

1. Provide a list or records of all severance agreements including severance amounts and agreement dates from July 1, 2023 through June 30, 2024. 
2. Provide a list or records of all settlements including settlement amounts and settlement dates from July 1, 2023 through June 30, 2024. 

Severance and Settlement may be used interchangeably and I do not want to exclude one or the other. This request is not limited to union settlements. 

This request is made on behalf of The FOIA Bakery. Because this request is in the public interest for Illinois nonprofit The FOIA Bakery’s work to advocate for public education, please waive any fees in accordance with 5 ILCS § 140/6(c). Feel free to contact me with any questions, or if clarification is needed. 

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes. 

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not. 

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires. 

Sincerely, 

Miriam Bhimani 

Upload documents directly: https://accounts.muckrock.com/accounts/login/?next=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.muckrock.com%2Faccounts%2Flogin%2F%3Fnext%3D%252Faccounts%252Fagency_login%252Fchicago-public-schools-3121%252Fsettlements-fy24-173745%252F%253F&url_auth_token=AAATZ164Jy60iQjs6iHTUOyYGcc%3A1stHjQ%3AZkp8GOWg2ADtq7JvZvYQodGN5kZDNnS3JJc3VpotzwY 
RESPONSE: Documents responsive to your request are available to download via the CPS FOIA Center at www.cps.edu/FOIARequests . Please log in with your username and password to access the records. To locate documents responsive to your request concerning settlements more than $100k, please visit the Chicago Board of Education website, and search the “Actions” links: https://www.cpsboe.org/meetings/past-meetings.  Student information has been redacted pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/7.5 (r) which exempts from inspection or copying information prohibited from being disclosed by the Illinois School Student Records Act (ISSRA). ISSRA generally prohibits the disclosure of “school student records” and defines a “school student record” as “any writing or other recorded information concerning a student and by which a student may be individually identified, maintained by a school or at is direction or by an employee of a school, regardless of how or where the information is stored.” (105 ILCS 10/2(d). You have a right to have the denial of your request reviewed by the Public Access Counselor (PAC) at the Office of the Illinois Attorney General. 5 ILCS 140/9.5(a). You can file your Request for Review with the PAC by writing to: Leah Bartelt; Public Access Counselor Office of the Attorney General 500 South 2nd Street Springfield, Illinois 62706 E-mail: public.access@ilag.gov 877-299-3642 You also have the right to seek judicial review of your denial by filing a lawsuit in the State circuit court. 5 ILCS 140/11. If you choose to file a Request for Review with the PAC, you must do so within 60 calendar days of the date of this denial letter. 5 ILCS 140/9.5(a). Please note that you must include a copy of your original FOIA request and this denial letter when filing a Request for Review with the PAC. Sincerely, Patricia Majchrowicz Freedom of Information Act Officer Chicago Public Schools

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Boehm Family Files (National Security Agency)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

I would like to read all of your files regarding myself and my immediate family, going back three generations, and any interactions we had with the covert side of the federal government.  My mother is Maureen Boehm nee Simpson, born 9/21/1947, and my father is Herman Boehm, born 4/7/1944.  My mother's father was Maurice Simpson, an Army scientist and unexploded ordinance technician in WWII, and my father's father was Herman Boehm, destroyer watch in WWII, captain of the buoy tender The Dahlia in the Coast Guard and one of the men who extinguished the Hindenberg.  My mother's mother was Doris Simpson nee Gardner and my father's mother was Adelaide Boehm.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Brian Boehm

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Request: Shimon Peres FBI
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

This is a request under the Freedom of Information Act.  I hereby request the following records:

Shimon Peres (Hebrew: שמעון פרס‎‎; born Szymon Perski; 2 August 1923 – 28 September 2016) was a Polish-born Israeli statesman. He was the ninth President of Israel, serving from 2007 to 2014. Peres served twice as the Prime Minister of Israel and twice as Interim Prime Minister, and he was a member of 12 cabinets in a political career spanning over 66 years. His death has been widely reported. http://www.nytimes.com/2016/09/28/world/middleeast/shimon-peres-dies-israel.html

Please conduct a search of the Central Records System, including but not limited to the Electronic Surveillance (ELSUR) Indices, the Microphone Surveillance (MISUR) Indices, the Physical Surveillance (FISUR) Indices, and the Technical Surveillance (TESUR) Indices, for both main-file records and cross-reference records.

I am a member of the news media and request classification as such. I have previously written about the Bureau for AND Magazine, MuckRock and Glomar Disclosure. My articles have been widely read, with some reaching over 100,000 readers. As such, as I have a reasonable expectation of publication and my editorial and writing skills are well established.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.


Sincerely,

Michael Best

title: Jenniffer González Colón Letters to USACE

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Jenniffer González Colón Letters to USACE
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Documents obtained through a FOIA sent to USACE's Jacksonville District, show that Jenniffer González Colón sent at least one letter to USACE in hopes of speeding up the approval of a Jurisdictional Determination (JD). The letter can be found here: https://www.documentcloud.org/documents/24805241-20230315-letter-gonzalez-colon-to-usace-jax?responsive=1&title=1

Therefore I request the following:

1) Every letter that Jenniffer González Colón or her office has sent to USACE's Jacksonville District. It's likely that these letters were sent to Col. James Booth, District Commander of USACE's Jacksonville District, and/or Mr. Howard Gonzales, Deputy District Engineer for Programs and Project Management for USACE's Jacksonville District.

Keywords: "Jenniffer González Colon" "tourism" "residential" "development" "JGO" "Puerto Rico"

This request is for all documents produced between January 1, 2022 and the time this request is processed.

This request is not being made for commercial purposes. I am an independent journalist and documents from this request will be used in the course of reporting about construction projects in Puerto Rico. https://muckrack.com/carlos-e-berrios-polanco

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Carlos Berríos Polanco

communications.subject: RE: [Non-DoD Source] Freedom of Information Act Request: Jenniffer González Colón Letters to USACE
communications.communication:
Good morning,

This message is in regard to a FOIA request you sent to our office on July 15, 2024.  You requested "every letter Jennifer Gonzalez Colon or her office has sent to USACE's Jacksonville District."  

There is something that must be addressed before the Jacksonville District can begin the search for the records you have requested. Your request for is considered impermissibly broad and does not comply with the FOIA's requirement that requests for records reasonably describe the records you are seeking. Your request, as written, would not allow professional agency employees familiar with the subject area to locate the records with a “reasonable amount of effort.”  It is the requester’s responsibility to identify the records they seek, and the records must be described in a manner that enables our record holders to locate the records with a reasonable amount of effort. Therefore, it is most helpful to us if a requester provides very specific, descriptive information about the records they seek. All of the records related to a Corps project are not maintained in a single file or location. Each office/department maintains its own records based on the issues or matters for which it is involved.  Additionally, present archival systems do not allow us to ensure an adequate search for records using such broad criteria. Therefore, for us to locate all "every letter Jennifer Gonzalez Colon or her office has sent to USACE's Jacksonville District" as instructed in your request, we would have to request that every employee within the Jacksonville District search all of their electronic and hard copy records located within their purview to see if they have records that relate in any way possible to your request. This type of extensive search would involve many employees and would involve many hours of search time.  Please provide more specific information so that a reasonable search for records can be done.  Our office will not be able to assist you with your request until you narrow the scope of what you are seeking.

We will keep this matter in a pending status, but if we don't receive an amended request by August 8, 2024, we will close the file and take no further action.

If you have any questions or need additional information, please let us know.

Thank you,

FOIA ADMINISTRATOR
U.S. Army Corps of Engineers, Jacksonville District
701 San Marco Blvd.
Jacksonville, FL 32207-8175
ph:  904-232-2477

ATTENTION:  PLEASE CONTACT OUR OFFICE DIRECTLY BY E-MAIL AT FOIA-SAJ@USACE.ARMY.MIL WITH ANY QUESTIONS OR CONCERNS. TO ENSURE YOUR REQUEST IS RECEIVED AND PROCESSED EXPEDITIOUSLY, IT IS RECOMMENDED THAT FOIA REQUESTS BE E-MAILED TO OUR OFFICE AT FOIA-SAJ@USACE.ARMY.MIL.

communications.subject: RE: Freedom of Information Act Request: Jenniffer González Colón Letters to USACE
communications.communication:
Hello,

Hope your day is going well.

Given that my request contains the person who sent the communication and the people most likely to have received them, what is the best way to narrow down my request so as not to burden your office? Would it be best I asked just to search the records of USACE Jacksonville's District Commander and District Engineer?

Best wishes,
Carlos
